topic.title: PCIe Analyzer Command

body.p: MRPC Command ID: 0x12

The PCIe analyzer is a per stack feature that monitors each port through port masking. It provides the capability to capture and store a maximum of 512 TLP headers. Additionally, the timestamp, sideband signals and some TLP markers are stored together with the TLP header for a total of 183 bits. A detailed break down of the PCIe Analyzer Header and Trigger Events can be viewed in PCIe Analyzer.
The analyzer RAM is a circular buffer with room for up to 512 TLPs than continuously overwrites old TLP headers. The analyzer RAM supports three types of trigger conditions:

li.p: TLP types that are also detected by AER (18 different supported types)

body.p: In the RST block, CAMs (IM, AR, ID, AT, NTL and MCL) can be used as a trigger source for the Analyzer RAM. When the CAM_ARAM_TRIG bit is set as a valid entry for one of the CAMs (IM, AR, ID, AT, NTL and MCL) and the TLP matches that rule entry, the Analyzer RAM will only trigger if the RST trigger is masked and analyzer RAM has started. The CAM_ARAM_TRIG bit is ORed with all matching CAM rules of a TLP allowing the analyzer RAM to trigger on any CAM this CAM_ARAM_TRIG set. A force trigger is also available on the analyzer RAM to force trigger on triggered events that have yet to occur.

When a capture terminates, the configured number of TLP headers are written into RAM after the event of a trigger. The TLP headers that are saved will remain valid before a new capture is initiated. The data can be repeatedly read out from the specified address of the analyzer RAM buffer.
The analyzer RAM contains the following five status types:
• ARAM_STATUS_IDLE - The analyzer RAM is in the idle state after FW initialization.
• ARAM_STATUS_STARTED - Analyzer RAM starts capture.
• ARAM_STATUS_STOPPED - Analyzer RAM stops capture.
• ARAM_STATUS_DATA_READY - The data captured from the triggered event is available and can now be dumped.
• ARAM_STATUS_STACK_INACTIVE - The analyzer RAM of the stack is inactive because its disabled in the configuration file for PM85XX less-port variants.

The analyzer RAM can be accessed on a per port basis from FW CLI or multiple MRPC hosts using access permissions. When the analyzer RAM module is free, a MRPC hosts or FW CLI can access the analyzer RAM when its granted an access permission. During this time, other MRPCs hosts or FW CLI will need to wait for the granted MRPC host or FW CLI to release the access permission from the port of the analyzer RAM.
For MRPC initiators, when the analyzer RAM is triggered, the analyzer RAM would perform an asynchronous notification to the host whereby the host can dump the status of the analyzer RAM.

table.title: TLP Analyzer Configuration Sub-Command Input Data

body.p: This field should be 0 for ARAM configuration.
Stack number.
Each bit points to one port of this stack. For example, bit 0 is for port 0, bit 1 is for port 1, and etc. Please note that the masked port should be active.
Each bit represents an event that will act as a trigger condition for ARAM.
Bit 0 - AER_UR_EN; Unsupported Request Error Enable. This is used only for received completion TLP with Unsupported Request status
Bit 1 - AER_ECRCERR_EN; ECRC Error Enable
Bit 2 - U_AER_MALTLP_EN; Malformed TLP Error Enable
Bit 3 - U_AER_RCVOVFL_EN; Receiver Overflow Error Enable
Bit 4 - AER_CA_EN; Completer Abort Error Enable. This is used only for received Completion TLP with Completion Abort status.
Bit 5 - AER_POITLP_EN - Poisoned TLP Error Enable
Bit 6 - U_AER_SDERR_EN - Surprise Down Error Enable
Bit 7 - U_AER_DLPERR_EN - Data Link Protocol Error Enable
Bit 8 - U_AER_HDRLGOVFL_EN - Header Log Overflow Error Enable
Bit 9 - U_AER_UINTERR_EN - Uncorrectable Internal Error Enable
Bit 10 - U_AER_RPTIMOUT_EN - Replay Timer Timeout Error Enable
Bit 11 - U_AER_RPNUMRO_EN - Replay Number Rollover Error Enable
Bit 12 - U_AER_BADDLLP_EN - Bad DLLP Error Enable
Bit 13 - U_AER_BADTLP_EN - Bad TLP Error Enable
Bit 14 - U_AER_RCVERR_EN - Receiver Error Enable
Bit 15 - AER_RCV_ERR_FATAL - Receive Fatal Error Message Enable
Bit 16 - AER_RCV_ERR_NON_FATAL - Receive Non-Fatal Error Message Enable
Bit 17 - AER_RCV_ERR_CORR_EN - Receiver Correctable Error Message Enable
Bit 18 - RST_EN - Rule Search Table Enable

This field indicates the additional number of TLP headers that is written into RAM after triggering. Please note this number does not include the TLP triggered Analyzer RAM and a value of 0 is not supported.

table.title: TLP Analyzer Operation Sub-Command Input Data

body.p: This field should be 1 to configure TLP Analyzer operation.
Stack number.
This field defines the following ARAM operations:

strow.stentry: Stops ARAM and prevents triggering on a configured condition
Starts ARAM to capture TLP and trigger on a configured condition
Force trigger on ARAM when it starts

body.p: “0” means stop ARAM thus ARAM would not trigger on the configured condition satisfied. “1” means start ARAM. Every time ARAM is configured, it should be started to capture TLP and trigger.

table.title: TLP Analyzer Status Dump Sub-Command Input Data

body.p: This field should be 2 to configure TLP Analyzer Status Dump.
Stack number.

table.title: TLP Analyzer Status Dump Sub-Command Output Data

body.p: This field defined the following Status of ARAM:
Stack ID in ARAM.
Current port mask setting.
Current TLP fill setting.
Current trigger mask setting.
The address of TLP trigger in ARAM. This field is valid only when ARAM is in DATA READY status (STATUS=3).
Start address of the TLP headers in ARAM buffer. This field is always 0 and only valid when ARAM is in DATA READY status (STATUS=3).
Number of valid TLP header in ARAM buffer. This field is only valid when ARAM is in DATA READY status (STATUS=3).
The number of TLP headers before the trigger cursor in the ARAM buffer. This field is only valid when ARAM is in DATA READY status (STATUS=3).

The number of TLP headers after the trigger cursor in the ARAM buffer. This field is only valid when ARAM is in DATA READY status (STATUS=3). Please note this field includes the TLP triggered the ARAM.

table.title: TLP Analyzer Data Dump Sub-Command Input Data

body.p: This field should be 4 for the TLP Analyzer Data Dump.
Stack number.
The address of the first TLP header to dump from the ARAM buffer.
The number of TLP headers to dump from the ARAM buffer. Please note due to the MRPC output buffer size limitation, only a maximum of 35 TLP headers per dump is supported.

table.title: TLP Analyzer Data Dump Sub-Command Output Data

body.p: The raw data of the TLP header. Please note that a header with DW#3 is invalid when TLP header is in 3 DWs format.
This field indicates whether an unaligned AER event has occurred between the previous and the current TLP for the associated port.
This field indicates whether an enabled aligned AER event is associated with the current TLP.
This field indicates whether an enabled RST routing rule match is associated with the current TLP.
This field indicates whether the current TLP is marked as a nullified TLP.
This field indicates whether the current TLP is marked as a TLP for discard.
This field indicates that the current TLP has a bad ECRC error.

This field indicates the sideband signals associated with the current TLP. Sideband signals can be valid at SOP or EOP. Those that are valid at SOP are first sampled on SOP and then written to the ARAM on EOP.
This field indicates the port number associated with the current TLP.
This field indicates the timestamp that supports 38 bits.
This field indicates if this TLP has been triggered.
The address of this TLP in ARAM buffer.

Write address 2048 with data: 18

stack 5, start ARAM to capture

Write address 2048 with data: 18

stack 5
